ying and sharing good practice. On 22 July, the Government published a FGM resource pack on gov.uk including examples of good local practice in Bristol informed by the Bristol Peer study.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates","HL3452 ; HL3453 ; HL3455","2014-12-19T16:21:21.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167932/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167932/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-12-04","Female Genital Mutilation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to the recommendations of peer studies on female genital mutilation, such as the Bristol PEER Study.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL3456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167933","Home Office","false","2014-12-19","<p>In response to Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary's (HMIC’s)report (March 2014) which exposed significant failings in the police response to domestic violence and abuse, the Home Secretary has established a National Oversight Group, which she is chairing, to drive delivery against all of the recommendations of the HMIC review.</p><p>To date, the Group has met three times. The Government has committed to publishing updates on the work of the National Oversight Group. The first report will be published shortly. A copy of the report will be placed in the libraries of both Houses.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2014-12-19T16:10:02.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167933/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167933/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-12-04","Domestic Abuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the reply by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 25 November (HL Deb, col 772), when the national oversight group chaired by the Home Secretary will report its findings, to whom it will report, and whether its findings will be published.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gale",,"Baroness Gale","HL3457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167934","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2014-12-15","<p>Abingdon Green is owned by the House of Commons, although its utilisation is managed by Black Rod. The House of Lords does not receive any income for temporary structures used by the media on College Green.</p>",,"Lord Sewel",,"2014-12-15T12:31:45.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167934/answer","Biography information for Lord Sewel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167934/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2014-12-04","Abingdon Green","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees how much income is received per year for permissions to the media for temporary structures on College Green.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167935","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-18","<p>The request will now be considered by the Court in line with the arrangements laid down in its rules of procedure. In accordance with those rules, if it does not decide to refuse the request the Court will refer it to the United Kingdom and invite written comments within a time-limit set by the Court.</p>",,"Lord Astor of Hever",,"2014-12-18T16:13:47.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167935/answer","Biography information for Lord Astor of Hever","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167935/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-12-04","Internment: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of allegations that information on alleged torture by United Kingdom forces in Northern Ireland was withheld from the European Court of Human Rights by the United Kingdom Government in 1971.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL3459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167937","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-01-13","<p>The average (median) rent of new Affordable Rent lets was £109 per week in England and £165 per week in London in 2013-14. These figures represent 80% of market rent across England and 55% of market rent in London.</p><p> </p><p>The Affordable Rent model allows for more new affordable housing to be delivered with lower levels of taxpayer capital subsidy and by levering in more private investment. The programme is helping deliver £15 billion of private investment in new affordable housing over the current spending review (2011-15), alongside £4.5 billion of public investment. Social rent and affordable rent go hand in hand; both help provide accommodation for those on low incomes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As the National Audit Office has observed: “the Department selected the best delivery model open to it for the funds it had available” and “the Department has so far achieved its policy objective to maximise the number of homes delivered within the available grant funding” (National Audit Office, “Financial viability of the social housing sector: introducing the Affordable Homes Programme”, 4 July 2012, HC465, pp. 6-7).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our Affordable Housing programme is set to deliver a further 275,000 new affordable homes between 2015 and 2020, levering in £38 billion of public and private investment.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-01-13T16:17:32.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167937/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167937/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167937/answer/previousversion/32530","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-12-04","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the average (a) rent and (b) proportion of market rent is of the homes built or converted as part of the affordable rent model.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","217193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167938","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-12-11","<p>Our records show that 217,000 new affordable homes have been delivered in England across all housing schemes since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>As has been explained to the hon. Member in answers to previous questions, this information is not broken down by (former) public land status.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-12-11T14:37:00.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167938/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167938/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-12-04","Affordable Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many affordable homes were completed on released public sector land sites in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013 and (e) 2014; and how many he expects to be built on such sites in 2015.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","217180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167939","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-03-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement of 16 March 2015, HCWS413.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","217185 ; 217196","2015-03-17T16:43:13.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167939/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167939/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167939/answer/previousversion/32531","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-12-04","Private Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many homes have been completed as a result of the private renting component of the Housing Bond Guarantee Scheme.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","217194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167940","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-02-25","<p>The Homes and Communities Agency’s Statistical Data Returns report the number of rental accommodation properties that have been converted to affordable rent. The figures relate to private registered provider owned stock only, and can be found online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases</a></p><p> </p><p>Detailed figures are not held centrally for local authority housing stock.</p><p> </p><p>The change in rental income from such conversions allows providers to borrow more to support the delivery of more new affordable homes.</p><p> </p><p>This Government has so far delivered 217,000 new affordable homes since 2010, and are bringing in £19.5 billion of public and private in affordable housing over the current Spending Review period. In the next Parliament, we are on track to deliver a further 275,000 new affordable homes, backed up by £38 billion of public and private investment.</p><p> </p><p>Conversions are not counted in these additional affordable homes figures.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-02-25T16:31:22.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167940/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167940/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167940/answer/previousversion/32532","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-12-04","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many homes have been converted to the Government's affordable rent model since it was introduced.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","217195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167942","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-02-23","<p>The Build to Rent fund provides development finance to support the creation of a purpose-built private rented sector, backed by institutional private investment. The fund offers finance on a commercial basis, with returns to Government being realised upon refinancing or sale of a developer’s interest to an institutional investor. The fund is market- led and the response has been strong.</p><p> </p><p>In the first round, the Homes and Communities Agency shortlisted 43 bids: 22 were approved subject to conditions being met (4 registered providers, 2 public limited companies, 12 private companies, 4 others); 16 bids were withdrawn during the process of scrutiny during the shortlisting; 5 bids from private companies were rejected.</p><p> </p><p>In the second round, 36 eligible bids were originally shortlisted (1 registered provider, 5 public listed companies, 26 private companies, 4 others); 3 private bids have been approved so far; the consideration of the other shortlisted bids is ongoing.</p><p> </p><p>We estimate that the Fund will this year be committed in full, and I can confirm that the programme is on course to meet our 10,000 homes target.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-02-23T16:54:54.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167942/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167942/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-12-04","Private Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many applications under the Build to Rent scheme have been (a) received, (b) accepted and (c) refused from (i) private developers, (ii) housing associations, (iii) housing co-operatives, (iv) local authorities and (v) other entities.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","217181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167943","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-12-16","<p>As has been explained to the hon. Member in the answer to her identical question of 8 January 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 257W, the Build to Rent fund is providing development finance to help support new homes in the private rented sector at market rent.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-12-16T17:20:42.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167943/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167943/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-12-04","Private Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many of the properties built under the Build to Rent scheme to date are (a) affordable, (b) social and (c) market rents.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","217182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167944","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-03-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement of 16 March 2015, HCWS413.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","217185 ; 217194","2015-03-17T16:43:13.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167944/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167944/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167944/answer/previousversion/32534","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-12-04","Housing Bond Guarantee Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many bids for funding the Government has received for the private renting component of the Housing Bond Guarantee Scheme.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","217196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167945","Department for Education","false","2014-12-11","<p>The Government is committed to eliminating illiteracy and wants all children to read easily, fluently and with good understanding. Our new English curriculum places a renewed focus on the requirement for pupils to learn to read through systematic synthetic phonics, as evidence shows this is the most effective approach to early reading. We do not have plans to introduce a national task force for literacy as we believe poor reading outcomes are best addressed through the implementation of the English curriculum and the other steps we have taken to improve literacy levels for all children, alongside measures to raise the attainment of disadvantaged pupils. The Department believes that good headteachers are best placed to support the needs of their pupils.</p><p> </p><p>To boost the quality of phonics teaching, we have provided £23.7 million in match funding to over 14,000 schools, enabling them to buy systematic synthetic phonics products and training. We have also introduced a phonics screening check. The first three years of the check have enabled teachers to identify nearly 568,000 six-year-olds who needed extra support.</p><p> </p><p>For pupils who do not reach the expected level in reading by the end of primary school, we have introduced the Year 7 Catch-up Premium. This funding – £500 per pupil – enables secondary schools to deliver additional support for those pupils that most need it.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also committed £8.8 billion of pupil premium funding for schools in England for the period between 2011-12 and 2015-16. The pupil premium gives schools the extra resources they need to close the attainment gap between those from poorer and wealthier backgrounds, including in reading outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>The 2014 Key Stage Two results show that our reforms are already having an effect: a record proportion of children (89%) reached the expected standard of reading (up three percentage points from last year). Attainment in reading has increased for disadvantaged pupils from 73% in 2011 to 78% in 2013, an increase of five percentage points.</p><p> </p><p>Unfortunately, pressures on the diary of my Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, mean she cannot promise to visit Bradford.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","217191 ; 217192","2014-12-11T17:43:38.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167945/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167945/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-12-04","Children: Literacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will set up an England-wide task force similar to the London Challenge to ensure that children who cannot read well are brought up to the required standard.","false","Biography information for Mr George Galloway","Bradford West","Mr George Galloway","217190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167946","Department for Education","false","2014-12-11","<p>The Government is committed to eliminating illiteracy and wants all children to read easily, fluently and with good understanding. Our new English curriculum places a renewed focus on the requirement for pupils to learn to read through systematic synthetic phonics, as evidence shows this is the most effective approach to early reading. We do not have plans to introduce a national task force for literacy as we believe poor reading outcomes are best addressed through the implementation of the English curriculum and the other steps we have taken to improve literacy levels for all children, alongside measures to raise the attainment of disadvantaged pupils. The Department believes that good headteachers are best placed to support the needs of their pupils.</p><p> </p><p>To boost the quality of phonics teaching, we have provided £23.7 million in match funding to over 14,000 schools, enabling them to buy systematic synthetic phonics products and training. We have also introduced a phonics screening check. The first three years of the check have enabled teachers to identify nearly 568,000 six-year-olds who needed extra support.</p><p> </p><p>For pupils who do not reach the expected level in reading by the end of primary school, we have introduced the Year 7 Catch-up Premium. This funding – £500 per pupil – enables secondary schools to deliver additional support for those pupils that most need it.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also committed £8.8 billion of pupil premium funding for schools in England for the period between 2011-12 and 2015-16. The pupil premium gives schools the extra resources they need to close the attainment gap between those from poorer and wealthier backgrounds, including in reading outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>The 2014 Key Stage Two results show that our reforms are already having an effect: a record proportion of children (89%) reached the expected standard of reading (up three percentage points from last year). Attainment in reading has increased for disadvantaged pupils from 73% in 2011 to 78% in 2013, an increase of five percentage points.</p><p> </p><p>Unfortunately, pressures on the diary of my Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, mean she cannot promise to visit Bradford.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","217190 ; 217192","2014-12-11T17:43:38.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167946/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167946/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-12-04","Children: Literacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the reasons for poor literacy among primary school children from (a) low income and (b) other families; what steps she is taking to ensure that all children are able to read well when they leave primary school; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr George Galloway","Bradford West","Mr George Galloway","217191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167950","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-12-09","<p>It has not been possible to answer this question within the timeframe. I will write to the Hon. Member in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-12-09T12:50:59.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167950/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167950/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-12-04","Local Criminal Justice Boards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the collection rate is for (a) fines, (b) prosecution costs, (c) compensation and (d) victims surcharge levied by each Local Criminal Justice Board in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","217172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167953","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-12-09","<p>Information on the number of claimants in receipt of personal independence payment, by a range of detailed breakdowns, has been published and can be found at: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Breakdowns by main disabling condition are currently available against 21 high level descriptors. From 17 December more detailed breakdowns of main disabling condition, including multiple sclerosis, will be available.</p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","217175","2014-12-09T12:23:52.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167953/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167953/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-12-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish or place in the Library a breakdown of personal independence payment by claimants' main disabling condition in a similar format to the information previously provided on disability living allowance claimants.","false","Biography information for Mr Russell Brown","Dumfries and Galloway","Mr Russell Brown","217178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167963","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-12-09","<p>The Government will set out our priorities for higher education for 2015-16 in the annual Grant Letter to the Funding Council.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-12-09T13:42:01.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167963/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167963/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-12-04","Higher Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to Annex 1 of his Department's grant letter to the Higher Education Funding Council for England for 2014-15, whether he plans to amend funding priorities for social mobility in higher education for 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","217152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167964","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-01-07","<p>Last year the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) funded the creation of a network of 27,000 accredited business mentors and partnered with the British Bankers Association (BBA) and Small Firms Enterprise Development Initiative (SFEDI) to create the mentorsme website. BBA and SFEDI now lead this initiative and have established a sector-led Enterprise Mentoring Advisory Council with responsibility for assessing the performance of the mentorsme website and the initiative overall.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Advisory Council also have responsibility for upholding the standards for enterprise mentoring, promoting awareness of the benefits of and access to enterprise mentoring and acting as a central policy advisory group.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>BIS has a seat on the Advisory Council and continues to support mentorsme by driving awareness and take up of mentoring as part of the national Business is GREAT campaign and by sharing research evidence and insight.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-01-07T11:29:15.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167964/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167964/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-12-04","Mentorsme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the performance of the Mentors Me website.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","217143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167965","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-12-09","<p>As required by section 9 of the Groceries Code Adjudicator Act 2013, the Adjudicator has consulted on a proposed maximum penalty, and has made a recommendation to the Secretary of State. This is currently the subject of cross-Government Ministerial consideration.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-12-09T15:00:20.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167965/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167965/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-12-04","Groceries Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he expects to bring forward delegated legislation to set the level of fine available to the Groceries Code Adjudicator.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","217158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167966","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-12-10","<p>This Government is committed to making Britain the best place in the world to start and grow a business. As part of our long term economic plan, we have thrown our weight behind small businesses as they grow our economy, create jobs for others and help communities prosper. In Milton Keynes an estimated 2,300 business have been started between November 2013 and October 2014, according to BankSearch data.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-12-10T15:04:30.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167966/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167966/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-12-04","New Businesses: Milton Keynes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many businesses have been started in Milton Keynes in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","217179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167967","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-12-10","<p>A preliminary equality impact assessment undertaken by the Department suggests there is little difference between the proportions of men and women undertaking postgraduate taught courses under 30 and those who are older, or in their propensity to study part-time. We will gather further evidence as part of the consultation before finalising the terms of the postgraduate taught loan.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-12-10T16:27:33.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167967/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167967/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167967/answer/previousversion/32556","Biography information for Greg Clark","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-12-04","Postgraduate Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what equality impact assessment in relation to gender his Department carried out on the proposal to limit the new postgraduate student loan finance to students under 30.","false","Biography information for Ann McKechin","Glasgow North","Ann McKechin","217197"
