"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167844","Department for Transport","false","2014-12-09","<p>The Secretary of State issued statutory guidance to the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in July 2012. Paragraph 24 provided guidance on access rights. A copy of the guidance is attached and can also be viewed on the GOV.UK website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3642/sos-guidance-to-orr.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3642/sos-guidance-to-orr.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>In August 2013 the Department responded to the ORR’s consultation, “Periodic Review 2013. On-rail competition: Consultation on options for change in open access”. A copy of the letter is also attached and it can be viewed on the ORR’s website at:</p><p><a href="http://orr.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/3752/on-rail-competition-dft.pdf" target="_blank">http://orr.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/3752/on-rail-competition-dft.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-12-09T15:35:52.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167844/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167844/answer","216597 - sos-guidance-to-orr.pdf ; 216597 - on-rail-competition-dft.pdf","216597 - sos-guidance-to-orr.pdf ; 216597 - on-rail-competition-dft.pdf","216957 - SoS letter to ORR ; 216957 - on-rail competition","216957 - SoS letter to ORR ; 216957 - on-rail competition","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167844/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-12-03","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department has issued to the Office of Rail Regulation on supporting more competition between franchised rail operators and open access rail operators where capacity and appropriate conditions exist.","false","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher","216957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167845","Department for Transport","false","2014-12-09","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to the answer I gave on 9 September 2014 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm140909/text/140909w0002.htm" target="_blank">208348</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-12-09T11:50:10.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167845/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167845/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-12-03","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to insulate his Departmental estate in order to improve energy efficiency; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","217051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167846","Department for Transport","false","2014-12-10","<p>The table below shows the capital grant allocations from the Department for Transport to Blackpool Council for the financial years 2010/2011 to 2014/15.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Allocation in £000s</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Capital Allocation</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Blackpool Tram Upgrade</p></td><td><p>38,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Integrated Transport block</p></td><td><p>8,241</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Highways Maintenance block</p></td><td><p>7,587</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pothole funding</p></td><td><p>181</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Local Pinch Point fund</p></td><td><p>2,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Severe Weather payments</p></td><td><p>440</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Better Bus Area Fund</p></td><td><p>1,032</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cycle Demonstration Town</p></td><td><p>775</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cycle Safety</p></td><td><p>133</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>59,809</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-12-10T10:57:36.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167846/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167846/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-12-03","Transport: Blackpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what capital investment allocations his Department has made to Blackpool Council since May 2010; what the value of those allocations was; and for what purpose each such allocation was made.","false","Biography information for Paul Maynard","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","217025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167847","Department for Transport","false","2014-12-08","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) conduct a number of different activities to monitor the quality of testing at MOT Garages. These range from re-inspecting vehicles that have just been tested through to conducting mystery shopper type activities.</p><p><br>DVSA use a mechanism to target its resource to those MOT Garages that present the greatest risk profile. The type of activity conducted is based on that which is best suited for the identified risk. These activities can range from an educative type support to a more stringent enforcement approach. <br><br>Where poor quality testing has been identified an assessment is carried out and, again, the approach is designed to be proportionate to the need - focused on best ensuring test quality. This could include on-site support or redirected additional training. More serious cases can result in the authorisation of either the Tester or the Authorised Examiner being removed from the scheme.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-12-08T16:46:31.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167847/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167847/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-12-03","Motor Vehicles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what checks are in place to ensure that MOTs are conducted properly; and what action is taken if they are not.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","217102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167848","Wales Office","false","2014-12-08","<p>The Department has taken steps to improve energy efficiency and is currently in the process of replacing its secondary glazing in its London office which will improve the insulation of the London building.</p><p>The Department’s Cardiff Office is in a modern building with built in energy efficiency measures.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2014-12-08T12:00:16.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167848/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167848/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-12-03","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps he has taken to insulate his Departmental estate in order to improve energy efficiency; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","217053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167849","Wales Office","false","2014-12-09","<p>Public procurement has the potential to create significant business and growth opportunities and I have met with leaders of the steel industry in Wales to discuss how the industry can best be supported by encouraging the use of domestic steel in UK Government contracts. I have also held discussions on the steel industry in Wales with the Minister of State at the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills as well as the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2014-12-09T11:33:51.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167849/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167849/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-12-03","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Welsh Government on the use of public procurement to support the steel industry in Wales.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","216999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167850","Women and Equalities","false","2014-12-10","<p>We are currently considering the form and timing of the public consultation in the light of ongoing caste discrimination litigation in the Employment Appeal Tribunal. We will await the outcome of the judgment before deciding in what form to issue the public consultation.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-12-10T16:38:50.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167850/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167850/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2014-12-03","Castes: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2014 to Question 209041, what assessment she has made of the implications of the findings of the final report on estimating the extent of caste-based discrimination in the UK on the timescale for the publication of a consultation on caste discrimination.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Mr Adam Holloway","217000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167851","Women and Equalities","false","2014-12-09","<p>We are currently considering the form and timing of the public consultation in the light of ongoing caste discrimination litigation in the Employment Appeal Tribunal. We will await the outcome of the judgment before deciding in what form to issue the public consultation</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-12-09T19:55:07.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167851/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167851/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167851/answer/previousversion/32604","Biography information for Nick Boles","31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2014-12-03","Castes: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2014 to Question 209041, when the final consultation on caste discrimination will be published.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","217135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167852","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-12-08","<p /> <p>The policy of this Coalition Government on the up-rating of UK state pensions paid to people living overseas is the same as that of successive post-war Governments. Namely to up-rate such pensions where we are legally required to under the terms of EU law or a bilateral social security agreement. There are no plans to change policy on this issue.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-12-08T16:34:06.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167852/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167852/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-12-03","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the potential merits of unfreezing state pensions for British citizens living in Commonwealth countries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","217127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167853","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-12-08","<p /> <p>A person who is entitled to Employment and Support Allowance and who does any work will normally be treated as not having limited capability for work and will lose their entitlement accordingly. However, under existing provisions, there are types of work that a claimant can do without losing their benefit entitlement.</p><p> </p><p>This is called ‘exempt work’ (more commonly referred to as ‘permitted work’). <br> The categories of exempt work are Permitted Work; Voluntary Work and work done in a Work Placement. There are four types of permitted work.</p><p> </p><p>· Permitted Work Lower Level: work for no more than £20 a week at any time for as long as the person is on benefit;<br> <br></p><p>· Permitted Work Higher Level: work for less than 16 hours a week with earnings of no more than £104.00 a week for a fixed period of 52 weeks with the aim of progressing to work of more than 16 hours per week; <br> <br></p><p>· Permitted Work Higher Level Subsequent: at the end of the 52 week period of PWHL, if they have not progressed to work of more than 16 hours, claimants can continue to work for no more than £20 per week. After a gap of 52 weeks customers can undertake a subsequent period of 52 weeks at the higher level;<br> <br></p><p>· Supported Permitted Work: claimants can work for no more than £104.00 a week for as long as they are on benefit if they have a disability which is unlikely to improve over time and they need regular and on going support or supervision in the work place in order to make as much progress as they can towards full-time work. A person is able to work and earn up to and including £104.00 a week indefinitely where their work is supervised by someone who is employed by a public or local authority, or a voluntary organisation whose job it is to arrange work for people with disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>A person can only do one type of Permitted Work at any one time and there are rules which cover the length of time that claimants may undertake each category, and the amount they can earn.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-12-08T12:24:20.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167853/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167853/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-12-03","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in what circumstances benefit claimants are permitted to undertake paid work which is regarded as therapeutic.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","217129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167854","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-12-08","<p>A person can do voluntary work as long as they do not receive any payment other than reasonable expenses. The work can be for a charitable or voluntary organisation, for example, or any other type of volunteering as long as it is not for a relative.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-12-08T12:35:05.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167854/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167854/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-12-03","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in what circumstances claimants of employment and support allowance are permitted to retain their benefit while undertaking voluntary work.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","217130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167855","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-12-08","<p /> <p>We believe that volunteering can play an important part in the life of unemployed people – not only by improving their chances of securing paid work but also through providing valuable support to their communities.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants can therefore do unlimited voluntary work whilst claiming benefits, providing they continue to meet all the usual entitlement conditions, although volunteers are allowed additional time to make themselves available for interviews and to take-up employment.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-12-08T17:17:26.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167855/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167855/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-12-03","Social Security Benefits: Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what arrangements his Department has in place with the voluntary sector to enable benefit claimants to undertake voluntary work.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","217131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167856","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-12-08","<p /> <p>The information as requested is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-12-08T12:48:54.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167856/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/167856/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-12-03","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who have been found fit for work following a work capability assessment have reapplied for employment and support allowance within (a) 12, (b) 24 and (c) 36 months.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","217123"
